## Migration: `Thread.Abort()` → Cooperative Cancellation

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+. The modern replacement is `CancellationToken` with `Task`-based execution.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// Callers should pass cancellation-aware delegates for best results.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Async overload — prefer this in new code
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Legacy shim — for work that can't accept a CancellationToken.
    // ⚠️ The work continues running in the background after timeout!
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        var task = Task.Run(work);

        if (task.Wait(timeout))
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult(); // re-throws inner exceptions
        }

        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forceful abort** | `CancellationToken` is *cooperative* — the work must check `token.IsCancellationRequested` or pass the token to APIs. Non-cooperative work **keeps running** after timeout. |
| **`ThreadAbortException` is gone** | Remove all `catch (ThreadAbortException)` / `ResetAbort()` blocks — they serve no purpose and won't compile against `ThreadAbortException` usage patterns. |
| **`default(T)` was hiding bugs** | The old code captured `result = default` then returned it. The new code propagates exceptions directly via `GetAwaiter().GetResult()`. |
| **`AggregateException` wrapping** | The old code manually wrapped in `AggregateException`. `Task` already does this — `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` unwraps to the original exception, which is usually what you want. |
| **Fire-and-forget leak** | The legacy shim lets timed-out work run indefinitely. Audit callers — if work holds locks, DB connections, or files, you *must* migrate to the `CancellationToken` overload. |
| **`Task.Wait` vs `WaitAsync`** | `.Wait(timeout)` blocks a thread. In async code use `.WaitAsync()` (available since .NET 6) to avoid threadpool starvation. |

### Caller Migration Example

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseQuery(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — pass the token through
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseQuery(ct), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// BEST — go fully async
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    ct => SlowDatabaseQueryAsync(ct), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**Bottom line:** `Thread.Abort()` was "stop it now, no matter what." .NET 8 requires cooperative cancellation — the work must opt in. Audit every call site to ensure the delegate actually respects the token, or the timeout becomes a lie.
